               <desc type="site-data" xml:lang="en">
                  <p source="#bibl000298-1">Occupying a total area of 30 square meters and oriented facing eastward , Xuankongsi (懸空寺) is an icon of the Mount Heng (恆山) area. Its name derived from its location on a cliff that stands between Mount Heng and Cuiping Peak (翠屏峰). The earliest construction of Xuankongsi dates back to the Northern Wei (北魏) dynasty. The site underwent significant renovations and additions during the Ming and Qing dynasties, whereby it assumed its current form. With forty bays of pavilions, palaces, and halls organized into a rectangular courtyard complex ten meters in length and three meters in width, the Xuankongsi complex can be divided into three sections – the monastery cloister (siyuan 寺院)the southern tower (nanlou南樓), and the northern tower (beilou北樓), all of which assume a different height from the ground level to conform to the overall geographical shape of the cliff. </p>
                  <p source="#bibl000298-2">The support structure of the Xuankongsi complex involves dozens of wooden beams underneath it. Soaked in tung oil (桐油) to prevent corrosion and worms, the beams were joined into mortise holes, whose depths are roughly half of the length of the beams, that are chiseled into the cliffside. The use of this timber joinery system not only supports the weight of the Xuankongsi complex, it is also believed to counteract the damage of natural disasters, such as earthquakes. </p>
               </desc>
